{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17586218","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17586218"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:28:20+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:28:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15078"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15078","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15078"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0,0,0.88,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7766"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66616"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7766","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7766"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15078"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52069"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"2948"},{"type":"tags","id":"3005"},{"type":"tags","id":"4183"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"6488"},{"type":"tags","id":"8115"},{"type":"tags","id":"8128"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18954"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18957"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22218"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66616","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66616"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EHaematuria is a common presenting complaint that requires risk stratification to guide appropriate investigation. Certain groups may need prompt attention with computed tomography urography and cystoscopy.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following groups would be most in need of this approach?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Asymptomatic patients","Low risk patients","Medium risk patients","High risk patients","Young patients"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe presence of risk factors significantly increases the probability of urological malignancy, particularly bladder cancer. Early detection through appropriate investigation of high-risk patients improves outcomes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERisk factors for urological malignancy include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESmoking history\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOccupational exposure to dyes or rubber\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPrevious urological malignancy\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPersistent or visible haematuria\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHigh risk patients\u003C/strong\u003E with haematuria require urgent investigation with both computed tomography urography and cystoscopy due to increased likelihood of underlying malignancy. \u003Cstrong\u003ELow risk patients\u003C/strong\u003E typically undergo less invasive initial investigations. \u003Cstrong\u003EMedium risk patients\u003C/strong\u003E may require tailored investigation pathways based on additional clinical factors. \u003Cstrong\u003EAsymptomatic patients\u003C/strong\u003E with incidental microscopic haematuria may need less urgent evaluation. \u003Cstrong\u003EYoung patients\u003C/strong\u003E without risk factors are more likely to have benign causes and may not require immediate invasive investigation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Visible haematuria in high-risk patients (age \u003E40, smoking history, occupational exposure) requires urgent investigation with computed tomography and cystoscopy.","Haematuria evaluation pathways are risk-stratified to balance cancer detection against investigation risks."],"references":["Rai BP, Luis Dominguez Escrig J, Vale L, Kuusk T, Capoun O, Soukup V, Bruins HM, Yuan Y, Violette PD, Santesso N, van Rhijn BWG, Hugh Mostafid A, Imran Omar M. Systematic Review of the Incidence of and Risk Factors for Urothelial Cancers and Renal Cell Carcinoma Among Patients with Haematuria. Eur Urol. 2022 Aug;82(2):182-192. doi: 10.1016/j.eururo.2022.03.027. Epub 2022 Apr 5. PMID: 35393159.","Lisanti CJ, Graeber A, Syed H, Moeck A, Rittel AG, Aden JK, Schwope R, Jellison F. What is the relative risk of urologic malignancy in microscopic hematuria patients after negative evaluation? A long-term population-based retrospective analysis of 8465 patients. Abdom Radiol (NY). 2023 Mar;48(3):1011-1019. doi: 10.1007/s00261-022-03793-x. Epub 2023 Jan 2. PMID: 36592198.","Jennette, J. C., \u0026 D\u0027Agati, V. D. (2023). Heptinstall\u0027s Pathology of the Kidney. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52069"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15078"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52069","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52069"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-01T16:07:41+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-01T16:08:10+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7766"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66616"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"